# README

# **Overview**

This project simulates an admin panel hypothesized to be the dashboard the client sees on their e-commerce platform, and it demonstrates how that platform can be integrated with HubSpot.

It uses the provided Express.js backend as a proxy to the HubSpot CRM API and a simple HTML/JavaScript frontend in \`/public\`.

The main scenarios covered are:  
\- View existing Contacts;  
\- Create new Contacts;  
\- View a Contact‚Äôs Deals (subscriptions);  
\- Create new subscriptions (Deals) for Contacts;  
\- Simulate a Thermostat purchase with or without a subscription plan and see how that is created in HubSpot.  
\- Simulate an AI action on HubSpot‚Äôs interface and have its response saved on a record‚Äôs property.

The next steps will address the setup required in order to be able to run the application locally, so you can observe the expected behavior when testing the flow of information between your current e-commerce platform and HubSpot.  
I recommend installing [Virtual Studio Code (VSC)](https://code.visualstudio.com/) before starting, as that‚Äôs a feature that easily allows you to edit part of the code that‚Äôs being provided here, which will be required in some steps.

# **Architecture Overview**

## **Components**

\- **Backend**  
  \- Node.js \+ Express server  
  \- Proxies to HubSpot using a Private App access token  
  \- Exposes REST endpoints under \`/api/...\`:  
    \- \`GET /api/contacts\`  
    \- \`POST /api/contacts\`  
    \- \`GET /api/deals\`  
    \- \`POST /api/deals\`  
    \- \`GET /api/contacts/:contactId/deals\`  
\- **Frontend**  
  \- Static HTML \+ vanilla JavaScript, served from \`/public/index.html\`  
  \- No frameworks, no build step  
  \- Talks to the backend only (not directly to HubSpot)

## **High-level flow** 

(how each component interacts with one another: Frontend \- Backend \- HubSpot)  
1\. **Frontend** calls \`/api/contacts\` and \`/api/contacts/:id/deals\` to render the UI.  
2\. When a user ‚Äúsimulates‚Äù an event (new customer creation, new subscription (deal), etc.), the frontend:  
   \- Calls \`POST /api/contacts\` or \`POST /api/deals\`  
   \- The **backend** makes the corresponding HubSpot CRM calls  
3\. HubSpot stores:  
   \- Contacts and their properties  
   \- Deals and their properties  
   \- Associations between Contacts and Deals

# **Prerequisites**

(how to have them installed/configured will be addressed in the A section)  
\- Node.js v14+    
\- npm or yarn (JavaScript package managers \- I use npm in this ‚Äútutorial‚Äù): they download all the libraries the project needs (which are pre-built code to run a few things)  
\- A free HubSpot account    
\- A HubSpot Private App with the following scopes:  
  \- \`crm.objects.contacts.read\`  
  \- \`crm.objects.contacts.write\`  
  \- \`crm.objects.deals.read\`  
  \- \`crm.objects.deals.write\`

# **3 ‚Äì Create a HubSpot private app, a custom property, and a workflow**

## 3.1 Create a private app

You‚Äôll need a **HubSpot sandbox/portal** (free is fine). This step enables you to generate an access token for the application to function properly.

\- Log into HubSpot.  
\- Go to Settings (gear icon on the top-right corner) ‚Üí Integrations ‚Üí Legacy Apps  
\- Create a Private App with the following scopes (name it with a name easy to identify):

* `crm.objects.contacts.read`  
  * `crm.objects.contacts.write`  
  * `crm.objects.deals.read`  
  * `crm.objects.deals.write`

After selecting the scopes above, click on ‚ÄúCreate app‚Äù. If you need more detailed guidance on how to create a Private app, please follow the guidelines in [this documentation](https://developers.hubspot.com/docs/apps/legacy-apps/private-apps/overview).

## 3.2 Create a custom property

\- Access your portal‚Äôs Settings (gear icon), and navigate to Data Management on the left menu \> Properties  
![][https://44580685.fs1.hubspotusercontent-na1.net/hubfs/44580685/README/image2.png]  
\- Under ‚ÄúSelect an object‚Äù, select Deals;  
\- Click on the ‚ÄúCreate Property‚Äù button, then select ‚Äúcreate manually‚Äù;  
\- In the UI, fill the property label with a name, it can be ‚ÄúAI Summary‚Äù, for example, and make sure that the selected object type is Deals;  
\- On the left menu, click field type, and in the drop-down on the page, select ‚Äúmulti-line text‚Äù;  
\- Click on the Create button (top-right corner);  
That will create a property that‚Äôs going to be used with the workflow below.

3.3 Create a workflow  
\- Access the automation area on your portal (the flowchart icon on the left menu of your portal);  
\- Click on ‚ÄúCreate workflow‚Äù on the top-right side of the page, and select ‚ÄúFrom scratch‚Äù;  
\- Under ‚ÄúData Values‚Äù, select ‚ÄúRecord created‚Äù \> Deal. On the left panel, click ‚ÄúNext‚Äù a couple of times until you see the ‚ÄúSave and Continue‚Äù button, and click on it to complete setting up the trigger;  
\- You‚Äôll see a square at the top, containing the trigger that you recently set up. Below it, there‚Äôs a little \+ (plus) sign; click it to set up an action;  
\- On the left panel, select AI \> then the ‚ÄúData Agent: Custom prompt‚Äù action. If that option is not available, please enroll your portal in this beta: https://app.hubspot.com/product-updates/\[YOUR\_PORTAL\_HUBID\_HERE\]/all?rollout=243904  
\- In the ‚ÄúWhat would you like to know?‚Äù text box, copy and paste the following prompt, then click Save:

```
You're reviewing a deal's information, like {{ enrolled_object.amount }}, {{ enrolled_object.hs_is_closed_won }}, {{ enrolled_object.hs_is_closed_lost }}, {{ enrolled_object.dealstage }}, {{ enrolled_object.hs_deal_score }}, in order to Summarize the customer‚Äôs subscription journey in plain English.

While doing it, highlight their current status: e.g. ‚ÄúOn Annual Breezy Premium with 2 thermostats; ACV ~$697.‚Äù
- Suggests one or two next actions for Sales/Marketing, like:
‚ÄúSend loyalty campaign.‚Äù
‚ÄúOffer discount for second thermostat.‚Äù
‚ÄúNudge to convert from free trial.‚Äù

- And any other suggestions that could be helpful from a Sales perspective, and you can also check past activities in the record's timeline
```

\- Below that action, click the \+ (plus) sign again, and go to the CRM section on the left panel;  
\- Select the ‚ÄúEdit record‚Äù action, and make sure the record type is set to ‚ÄúDeal (current object)‚Äù;  
\- In the ‚Äúproperty to edit‚Äù field, select the ‚ÄúAI Summary‚Äù property you created on the previous step; that will open a text box below it;  
\- Click on the text box, and in the slide-in menu that is displayed (you‚Äôll see ‚Äúall data tokens‚Äù at the top of it), select ‚ÄúData Agent: Custom prompt‚Äù \> then the ‚ÄúResponse‚Äù option. Save.  
\- At the top-right corner, click on ‚Äúreview and turn on‚Äù \> ‚Äúskip to turn on‚Äù (at the bottom of that right side panel) \> Turn on workflow.

# **B \- Project Overview**

This proof of concept demonstrates how Breezy company could integrate its e-commerce and subscription management platform almost seamlessly with HubSpot‚Äôs CRM.

This POC includes three core capabilities:

## 1\. Customer Creation & De-duplication

A unified form that simulates a Breezy customer signing up and purchasing a thermostat and subscription. The system also checks if the customer already exists in HubSpot by their email:

- If the email exists ‚Üí the existing contact is reused;  
- If not ‚Üí a new contact is created;

This prevents duplicates while keeping HubSpot as the single source of truth.

## 2\. Subscription Deal Creation (with Contract Value Calculation)

After identifying/creating the customer, the app automatically creates a subscription deal in HubSpot:

- Supports Free, Monthly, or Annual plans;  
- Monthly plans are converted to a 12-month contract value (ACV), which makes it easier for the finance department to keep track of revenue;  
- Optional thermostat hardware is included as a simulated line item. The ‚Äúoptional‚Äù part exists in case the subscription is renewed without an extra thermostat purchase;  
- The final deal amount reflects the combined subscription value and hardware value, giving Breezy accurate revenue data.

## 3\. CRM Synchronization & Reporting Visibility

The UI displays:

- A list of contacts pulled directly from HubSpot;  
- Their associated deals (subscription and hardware purchases);  
- A full deal history for any selected customer (up to 50 deals);

This allows Breezy to view customer lifecycle data exactly as it would appear inside HubSpot CRM.

## 4\. Use of a native AI feature

- By using the ‚ÄúAI Summary‚Äù custom property and filling it with the assistance of our native Data Agent feature, this POC also demonstrates how helpful and versatile our AI tools can be.  
- The use of native AI tools helps save extra resources and custom integration development, while also keeping most data management centralized in HubSpot.

Overall, the POC demonstrates how Breezy could centralize customer purchases, maintain accurate subscription revenue, and represent product \+ subscription data inside HubSpot using a clean, secure, API-based integration, plus making use of our native AI features. The fact that this would have data centralized in one place, with AI providing helpful insights based on it, is a great asset to assist their sales and marketing teams in focusing efforts depending on contacts‚Äô segments that they can organize within HubSpot.

# **D. HubSpot Data Architecture**

1. ## Entity Relationship Diagram (ERD)

![][https://44580685.fs1.hubspotusercontent-na1.net/hubfs/44580685/README/image5.png]  
The application developed here focuses mostly on the relationship between the Contact and the Deal (Subscription), with a mock version of adding ‚ÄúLine Items‚Äù (in the ‚Äúsubscription details‚Äù area in the UI‚Äôs form) \- the idea would be to completely integrate the hardware and subscription as line items for better revenue tracking.  
I also added a possible improvement to the integration, to create a custom object (the thermostat) and a subscription (which would relate to the line item as I mentioned above). This could further centralize all their information in HubSpot, making it easier to manage all their data.

2. ## Deal Pipeline Architecture

I simply used the guidelines provided, using default values that make the UI display the stages as follows:

* appointmentscheduled \- Trial started \-\> shows as Appointment Scheduled in Hubspot  
* qualifiedtobuy \- Active trial user \-\> shows as Qualified to Buy in Hubspot  
* closedwon \- Converted to paid subscription \-\> shows as Closed Won in Hubspot

For this step, I opted to use HubSpot‚Äôs AI native feature. The idea here is to have our AI native feature provide the client with an example of how our Data Agent can scan a record‚Äôs information \- I focused on properties like the Amount spent, if it‚Äôs Won or Lost, current stage and its Score (if set up) \- and provide some insights related to that deal in order to assist the sales team by providing some possible approaches to the contact associated with the deal \- call/meeting suggestions, engage via email to convert a free trial, etc.

# **F. Design Decisions**

For creating contacts and subscription deals, I chose to place all customer inputs into a single unified onboarding form \- I assumed that when a client is going through the purchase process, their e-commerce system collects both the contact and subscription information, and saves it as a type of record on their platform. This mirrors how Breezy might onboard customers in real life. Combining these two steps into one form reduces friction and ensures all data stays consistent.  
However, that generated an issue when filling the form again if a contact already existed, so I had to ask ChatGPT for a ‚Äúcode improvement‚Äù to verify if the contact already existed, and in that case the request would only acknowledge the contact‚Äôs existence (in the form of an error in the server‚Äôs Terminal), ignore a duplicate creation, but it would still create and associate a new deal with the existing contact.

To accomplish the above, I asked ChatGPT to add an **email de-duplication** rule using HubSpot‚Äôs Search API, making HubSpot the source of truth for customer data. Preventing duplicate contacts ensures cleaner CRM data and avoids breaking functionalities. If the email already exists, the request simply shifts from ‚Äúnew customer onboarding‚Äù to ‚Äúnew subscription event,‚Äù which reflects real customer behavior.

I assumed Breezy has both a **hardware component** (smart thermostats) and a **software subscription service** (Breezy Premium, though optional). Because the assessment text mentions trial users, subscription upgrades, and conversions, I treated the subscription as the primary revenue driver and the thermostat hardware as a one-time purchase.

For subscription pricing, I stored a **12-month contract value** for Monthly plans, because Breezy likely tracks ARR/ACV rather than monthly cash flow. I also asked the AI to include the calculated thermostat hardware value in the UI and included it in the total deal amount \- for the form‚Äôs UI, still, that was to simulate a client purchasing the hardware, and possibly the subscription, the idea was to try and make this as plausible as possible with the information I had, plus what I was asusming. Even though I simulated the hardware as a UI-only line item, this reflects an approach Breezy could take to represent product revenue within a subscription lifecycle (also added to the ERD‚Äôs ‚Äúimprovement‚Äù plan).

In a real meeting with the client, I would make efforts to collect more data related to the e-commerce platform and how it works, their clients' purchase process, and subscription details (can a client have multiple thermostats and only one subscription, or is the subscription really tied to a single thermostat?

If I had more time, I would also add **real line items** in HubSpot instead of handling hardware and subscription values only in the UI. This would allow deals to reflect product SKUs and subscription SKUs separately, which is better for revenue reporting and forecasting inside HubSpot. Creating a custom Thermostat object would also provide them with better hardware management \- expected maintenance, device‚Äôs lifetime, model and serial number, etc., all centralized in HubSpot.

I would also focus on implementing a different **AI-powered insight**, based on information tracked by their paid subscription, as mentioned in the assessment‚Äôs scenario: AI-powered climate optimization, Energy usage analytics, Remote access and scheduling, Integration with other smart home devices.

And finally, I would ask them what their long-term objective is while using HubSpot, and what they expect the platform can help them achieve during that time.
